She flipped to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Are you bringing up old memories?" asked Ivory and looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari out, as he considered her a "blemish." She was born deaf and was the only daughter of the family, her siblings were all boys.
Something similar applied to Ivory. When Ivory came out as nonbinary, it seemed as though the world changed too. As punishment for this difference, Ivory received tasks that kept them mostly alone.
Moreover, Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't bother Ivory much, since Ivory gained a friend.
"You're having a birthday soon, right?" asked Ivory, thinking that the princess would have a birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad flicker in her bright blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate your birthday?" asked Ivory, thinking of the last time the princess had answered this question.
"No," tapped Kari. Ivory knew this was a difficult subject for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory had been a baby at the time but remembered how upset the servants and the city's residents had been. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a beloved queen, and strangely enough, she could also predict things that actually came true.
"Well, what would you like to do?" asked Ivory. Kari looked at Ivory excitedly. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
Knows, various shades of blue
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
"Are these things I'm supposed to get for you?" Ivory addressed the silent princess, whose braids swayed back and forth from her vigorous tapping. "Yes?" Ivory chuckled softly. The usually reserved princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! See you later?" Ivory asked, got up, and slung her way through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her bedsheet.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess had finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, like malachite.
Ivory ran through the corridors again and tried to ignore the servants' gossip.
"I've heard that she is supposed to be possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going into this room again and again."
"I've heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, that's not normal, is it?"
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn't ignore the gossip and continued on. The royal painter's room was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as elaborately decorated as Kari's door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons said to have supposedly created Frostfell. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door certainly made sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual mess. Paint splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered throughout the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Unexpectedly, however, a different sight presented itself. The entire room was clean, and in front of a red velvet background stood a chair. Sitting on the chair was Crown Prince Aquilo, who was currently being portraitured.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch how your future king is being portraitured?" Aquilo asked, winking at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," said Ivory, largely ignoring him and gathering the things the silent princess desired. "I'm only here to get art supplies."
"Is my little girl already leaving?" asked Aquilo. "But I would like you to stay!"
"I am not, however." Ivory found the art supplies on the list and placed them in a box. "Besides, I am not a girl."
The prince, however, had a different opinion. "Oh sweetie, that's just a phase! As you get older, you'll grow out of it!" he said indistinctly.
"I have to go," said Ivory, feeling uncomfortable with the prince's answer. Ivory was reminded of all the ugly remarks he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past. I just want to get away from here.
"You're already leaving?" Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
"That's no behavior for a future king!" said Ivory.
"Nobody will find out. People won't believe you, and the painter will keep quiet if his life is worth anything to him." He glanced at the painter for a moment before leaning closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?" Ivory had been harassed in the past, but never by a prince, and certainly not by the crown prince.
"Do you actually know what the word 'no' means?" Ivory spat and pushed the crown prince away from her.
"No," answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have anything he wants, doesn't know what the word "No" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have around 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which swirled around in the cold air.
"Now come on, get it! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced Ivory to look at him.
